    <part id="openclaw">
      <title>OpenClaw</title>
      <slide id="what-is-openclaw">
        <title>What is OpenClaw?</title>
        <!--<img src="openclaw-logo.png" style="float: right ; max-height : 60% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; "/>-->
        <ol>
          <li><em>A persistent, self-improving AI agent</em></li>
          <li><em>Multi-channel and multi-agent</em></li>
          <li><em>API-native by design</em></li>
        </ol>
        <img src="openclaw-logo.png" class="fullsize" style="max-height : 25%"/>
      </slide>
      <slide id="what-are-universal-agents">
        <title>The Age of Universal Agents</title>
        <img src="universal-agents.png" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
      </slide>
      <slide id="mcp-and-more">
        <title>Don't bet everything on MCP!</title>
        <img src="MCP-APIs-All-The-Way-Down.jpeg" style="float: right ; height : 60% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; filter: drop-shadow(0px 0px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.6)) ; "/>
        <ol>
          <li>APIs are the real foundation</li>
          <li>MCP is an entry, but it's really APIs all the way down</li>
          <li>OpenClaw prefers direct API / CLI access - the shortest path</li>
          <li>No API, No party!</li>
        </ol>
      </slide>
    </part>
    <part id="api-first">
      <title>API First</title>
      <slide id="api-first-10">
        <title>API First 1.0: Developer Experience (DX)</title>
        <ul>
          <li><em>Don't break consumers:</em> Design a contract and stick to it</li>
          <li><em>Speed up delivery:</em> API providers and consumers work in parallel</li>
          <li><em>API products:</em> Design APIs instead of exposing implementations</li>
          <li><em>Scalable Governance:</em> Implementation-independent APIs live longer</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="optionality">
        <title>Optionality: Unbundling the Enterprise with APIs</title>
        <img src="unbundling-the-enterprise.jpg" title='Stephen Fishman and Matt McLarty, "Unbundling the Enterprise: APIs, Optionality, and the Science of Happy Accidents", 2024' style="float: right ; height : 70% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ;  filter: drop-shadow(0px 0px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.6)) ; "/>
        <ul>
          <li>Build up capabilities for experimentation and discovery</li>
          <li>APIs are the foundational layer of digital capabilities</li>
          <li><q>API First</q> builds everything as digital building blocks</li>
          <li>Optionality is a potent accelerant for AI success</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="dx-ax">
        <title>From DX to Agent Experience (AX)</title>
        <ul>
          <li>2000s: Having any API is good</li>
          <li>2010s: Having many APIs is good</li>
          <li>2020s: Having many developer-friendly APIs is good</li>
          <li>2025: Having many machine-friendly APIs is good</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-first-20">
        <title>API First 2.0: From DX to AX</title>
        <ul>
          <li><em>AI needs capabilities:</em> AI cannot do anything without APIs → ✅</li>
          <li><em>Runtime discovery/usage:</em> Find and use APIs when needed → 🎥</li>
          <li><em>Workflows:</em> Make workflows part of the API strategy → 🎥</li>
          <li><em>Agent risk management:</em> Limit blast radius with APIs → 🎥</li>
          <li><em>Sandboxes:</em> Create a safe space for agents to experiment in → 🎥</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
    </part>
    <part id="ax">
      <title>Agent Experience (AX)</title>
      <slide id="dx-homework">
        <title>Do Your DX Homework</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Most API descriptions need quality improvements anyway</li>
          <li>Better descriptions benefit <em>everyone</em>, not just AI agents</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Complete and meaningful operation summaries</li>
            <li>Comprehensive examples for all operations</li>
            <li>Clear error handling</li>
            <li>Consistent terminology and naming</li>
          </ul>
          <li>Good DX is the foundation for good AX</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="ax-homework">
        <title>Now There's AX Homework, Too</title>
        <img src="robot.png" style="float: right ; height : 80% ; margin : 0% 0% 0% 0% ; "/>
        <ul>
          <li>AI agents need information developers don't typically require:</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Everything that developers usually <q>just know</q></li>
            <li>Treat every API like an external one for developers with no context</li>
          </ul>
          <li>OpenAPI Initiative (OAI) might add AX-specific fields</li>
          <li>Until then, leverage description fields strategically</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
    </part>
    <part id="scoring">
      <title>API Scoring for AI Readiness</title>
      <slide id="what-agents-need">
        <title>What AI Systems Actually Need</title>
        <p>Agents need APIs to be:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Discoverable:</strong> able to find and classify API</li>
          <li><strong>Interpretable:</strong> intent must be explicit</li>
          <li><strong>Composable:</strong> clear inputs / outputs</li>
          <li><strong>Safe:</strong> authNZ &amp; safety signals machine readable</li>
          <li><strong>Predictable:</strong> idempotency, stable responses</li>
          <li><strong>Resilient:</strong> clear signals for success and failure</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="what-agents-need">
        <title>You Can't Improve What You Can't Measure</title>
        <img src="API-AI-Measurements.png" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
        <p style="text-align: center;">AI-readiness starts with understanding your current API landscape</p>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-ai-readiness-framework">
        <title>API AI-Readiness Framework</title>
        <p style="text-align: center;">Evaluates APIs across six human &amp; AI-readiness dimensions</p>
        <img src="api-ai-readiness-dimensions.png" href="https://github.com/jentic/api-ai-readiness-framework" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
        <p style="text-align: center;">See: <a href="https://github.com/jentic/api-ai-readiness-framework">https://github.com/jentic/api-ai-readiness-framework</a></p>
      </slide>
      <slide id="ai-readiness-scorecard">
        <title>AI-Readiness Scorecard</title>
        <img src="api-ai-scorecard.png" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
        <p style="text-align: center;">See: <a href="https://jentic.com/scorecard">https://jentic.com/scorecard</a></p>
      </slide>
      <slide id="foundational-compliance">
        <title>Foundational Compliance</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Evaluates if an API is structurally valid, standards-compliance, and parseable by tooling.</li>
        </ul>
        <br/>
        <table rules="all" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" width="80%" style="border: 2px solid #ABC9CB; margin-left: 3em;">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th valign="bottom" style="background-color: #385155; color: #ffffff; font-weight: bold; text-align: left;">Signal</th>
              <th valign="bottom" style="background-color: #385155; color: #ffffff; font-weight: bold; text-align: left;">Description</th>
              <th valign="bottom" style="background-color: #385155; color: #ffffff; font-weight: bold; text-align: left;">Normalisation</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Spec Validity</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">Checks whether the API parses as a valid OpenAPI</td>
              <td valign="top">binary</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Resolution Completeness</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">What proportion of $ref references successfully resolve</td>
              <td valign="top">coverage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Lint Results</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">Aggregated quality score from linter diagnostics, weighted by severity</td>
              <td valign="top">inverse weighted categorical</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Structural Integrity</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">Measures whether the API's underlying data model is coherent enough for automated reasoning (semantic or logical defects that impact reliable interpretation)</td>
              <td valign="top">logarithmic dampening</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </slide>
      <slide id="foundational-compliance">
        <title>Foundational Compliance - Structural Integrity</title>
        <ul>
          <li><code>structural_integrity = max(0, 1 - log10(1 + structural_issues) / log10(1 + structural_issue_threshold))</code></li>
        </ul>
        <img src="structural-integrity-signal.png" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
      </slide>
      <slide id="ai-discoverability">
        <title>AI Discoverability</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Evaluates how easily AI systems can locate, classify, and route to the API across registries, workflows, and knowledge bases.</li>
        </ul>
        <br/>
        <table rules="all" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" width="80%" style="border: 2px solid #ABC9CB;  margin-left: 3em;">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th valign="bottom" style="background-color: #385155; color: #ffffff; font-weight: bold; text-align: left;">Signal</th>
              <th valign="bottom" style="background-color: #385155; color: #ffffff; font-weight: bold; text-align: left;">Description</th>
              <th valign="bottom" style="background-color: #385155; color: #ffffff; font-weight: bold; text-align: left;">Normalisation</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Descriptive Richness</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">Evaluates the semantic value of textual descriptions within an API description</td>
              <td valign="top">coverage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Intent Phrasing</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">Evaluates verb-object clarity of summaries and descriptions</td>
              <td valign="top">semantic similarity</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Workflow Context</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">Evaluates indicators to workflow specifics including Arazzo/MCP/workflow references. Also analyses existence of callbacks etc.</td>
              <td valign="top">coverage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Registry Signals</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">Detects metadata related to API gateways, llms.txt, APIs.json, MCP registries, externalDocs links to Dev portals</td>
              <td valign="top">coverage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="vevent">
              <td valign="top" style="font-weight: bold;"><b><code>Domain Tagging</code></b></td>
              <td valign="top">Detect domain/taxonomy classification through the use of tags</td>
              <td valign="top">coverage</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </slide>
      <slide id="ai-discoverability-impact">
        <title>API Discoverability - Do it for the Agents (and your teams)!</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Better Signal Scores = Better APIs = Better Searchability </li>
          <li>Improved results in vanilla and specialized search offerings </li>
          <li>Using expensive models doesn't fix bad API semantics </li>
          <li>Save yourself the trouble and the $$$</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="ai-readiness-deep-dive">
        <title>API AI-Readiness Framework: Deep Dive</title>
        <img src="YouMayHaveOpenAPI.jpg" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qzeR4wBcS4s" title="You May Have OpenAPI, But Is It AI-Ready - from APIDays Paris Dec 2025" class="fullsize"/>
        <p style="text-align: center;">See: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qzeR4wBcS4s">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qzeR4wBcS4s</a></p>
      </slide>
    </part>
